@matthew-brett Thanks for your input. I think you are misunderstanding, as we're not talking about relying on travis virtualenv, rather the python *version* (2.7.9) that ships in their virtualenv. In other words, not using system python (2.7.3). This is only applies to the python 2.7 test, as we never have (as I'm aware of) installed system python 3 and tested with that. The implication is that we cannot use system packages, and if we want to test against PIL, we need to provide a package for that (preferably a wheel package).

Though I understand your point, both @matthew-brett and @blink1073, about not relying on travis env, I must say it's a bit strange. Any package changes in the env that are within our requirements should pass the tests. Also, if installing some non-requirement break the build, I say that's worth looking into. I might be wrong though, I have not investigated your trouble with using travis env earlier.

Regarding `--trusted-host`, that's another issue than the main obstacle here (a `pkg_resources` conflict between system and travis python 2.7). You are correct though, `--trusted-host` is required whenever pip in the venv upgrades to 7.0.

