Sorry if this is out of scope, but concerning Flask-Restless I'd suggest that a way to improve a bit is allowing multiple errors on a field. Instead of `'field': 'error description'`, it could be `'field': ['error description', 'Another error description']` The example on [doc](http://flask-restless.readthedocs.io/en/stable/customizing.html#capturing-validation-errors) would be something like this:
```
HTTP/1.1 400 Bad Request
{ "validation_errors":
    {
      "age": ["Must be an integer", "Must be positive"],
    }
}
```
I have just arrived to SAValidation following the Flask-Restless documentation, therefore, I don't really know right now whether it performs some kind of multiple field validation and how it is done. I haven't thought thoroughly about this, but maybe a possible representation of this could be done using some kind of composed key. For example, consider a poor representation of a Person where their age and their birthday are stored and somehow it is checked whether they are coherent (I know that the example is silly, but it is an easy way to show what I'm proposing):
```
HTTP/1.1 400 Bad Request
{ "validation_errors":
    {
      "age": ["Must be an integer", "Must be positive"],
      "multifield_age__birthday": ["Are you lying about your age or your birthday?"]
    }
}
```

